## Key Decisions & Rationale

### Why API extraction instead of image tracing?

| Approach | Accuracy | Time | Scalability |
|----------|----------|------|-------------|
| Manual screenshot tracing | ~70-80% (pixel imprecision) | Days | None — redo for any update |
| **API extraction** | **~99.9%** (official source data) | **Minutes** | **Re-run script anytime** |

### Why `bndry_jsn` over `poly_fnce_tx`?

Both contain the same coordinates. `bndry_jsn` is already a JSON array, requiring only a coordinate-order swap. `poly_fnce_tx` is WKT text requiring regex parsing of `POLYGON((lng lat, lng lat, ...))`.

### Why AES-256-CBC with SHA-256 key derivation?

This is the encryption scheme the CDMA portal uses. The JWT token string is hashed with SHA-256 to produce a 32-byte key, and the IV is transmitted alongside the ciphertext in base64 encoding. This is a common pattern for "light" encryption of public data APIs — it prevents casual scraping but the key is embedded in the client-side JavaScript.

---

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Reusability:** The `fetch_geojson.py` script can be re-run anytime to refresh boundary data if the CDMA portal updates. The JWT token has an expiry (`exp: 1751883880` ≈ July 2025), so a new token may need to be extracted from the website's JavaScript if it expires.
